DECtalk''' was a [[speech synthesizer]] and [[text-to-speech]] technology developed by [[Digital Equipment Corporation]] in 1984,<ref name=dectalkpreannounce1984 /> based largely on the work of [[Dennis H. Klatt|Dennis Klatt]] at [[MIT]], whose source-filter algorithm was variously known as KlattTalk or MITalk.<ref name=klatt> {{citation | last = Klatt | first = Dennis | date = April 1987 | title = How Klattalk became DECtalk: An Academic's Experiences in the Business World | periodical= The official proceedings of Speech Tech '87<!-- : Voice Input/Output Applications Show and Conference, April 28-30, 1987, New York City, at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel --> | url = http://searchworks.stanford.edu/view/6824203 | publisher = Media Dimensions Inc./Penn State | location = New York | pages = 293–294
}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=f2_sPyfVG3AC&lpg=PA42&pg=PA42#v=onepage Computer talk: amazing new realism in synthetic speech], By T. A. Heppenhemimer, Popular Science, Jan 1986, Page 42 and 44 and 48, ''..with the creator of DECtalk, Dennis Klatt...Ironically having given computers the power of speech, he slowly losing his own...DECtalk - actually a micro computer itself -...''</ref>
==About== The first DECtalk units were seen in 1984. They were standalone units that connected to any device with an [[asynchronous serial communication|asynchronous]] [[serial port]]. These units were also able to connect to the telephone system by having two telephone jacks. One connected to a phone line, the other to a telephone. The DECtalk units could recognize and generate any telephone [[touch tone]]. With that capability the units could be used to automate various telephone-related tasks by handling both incoming and outgoing calls. This included acting as an interface to an email system and the capability to function as an alerting system by utilizing the ability to place calls and interact via touch tones with the person answering the phone.
Later units were produced for PCs with [[Industry Standard Architecture|ISA]] bus slots. In addition, various software implementations were produced, most notably the DECtalk Access32. Certain versions of the synthesizer were prone to undesirable characteristics. For example, the [[alveolar stop]]s were often assimilated as sounding more like [[dental stop]]s. Also, versions such as Access32 would produce faint electronic beeps at the end of phrases.
In the [[Digital Equipment Corporation#Final years|final years of DEC]], early/mid-2000,<ref> {{cite press release | title = AllLinuxDevices: Force to Support Linux On DECtalk TTS For Strongarm and Intel Devices | url = http://www.linuxtoday.com/infrastructure/2000102600720PREM | work = Linux Today | date = 2000-10-26 | accessdate= 2012-09-16 }} </ref> the DECtalk IP was sold to Force Computers, Inc. In December 2001, the IP was sold<ref> {{cite news | title = Fonix acquires DECtalk from Force Computers | url = http://www.deseretnews.com/article/880848/Fonix-acquires-DECtalk-from-Force-Computers.html?pg=all | work = Deseret News | date = 2001-12-21 | accessdate= 2012-09-16 }} </ref> from Force Computers, Inc, to Fonix Speech, Inc. (now [[SpeechFX|SpeechFX, Inc.]]), which offers DECtalk as a small-footprint [[Text-to-speech|TTS]] system.<ref> {{cite web | title = SpeechFX Text to Speech Solutions, FonixTalk, DecTalk | url = http://www.speechfxinc.com/text-to-speech.html#dectalk | publisher = SpeechFX, Inc. | accessdate= 2012-05-25 }}</ref>
==In technology and culture== *The DECtalk engine was notably used in the US [[National Weather Service]]'s first "Console Replacement System" (CRS) installations in the late 1990s for [[NOAA Weather Radio]]. {{as of|2003}} it had all but been replaced by a far more modern engine called [[Speechify]]. The so-called "Perfect Paul" voice (a DECtalk "preset" for a default understandable male voice) still does [[Station identification]]s on many NWR stations.<ref> {{cite web | title = NOAA Weather Radio Automated Voice and Programming | url = http://www.nws.noaa.gov/nwr/nwrcrs.htm | publisher = NOAA | location = USA | accessdate= 2013-06-09 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131014052527/http://www.nws.noaa.gov/nwr/nwrcrs.htm | archivedate=2013-10-14 }}</ref> *One of the early uses was a "text to voice" system that read an individual's emergency medical information (medications, allergies, doctor, insurance and contact info stored in a database) to hospitals telephoning in about patients presenting at emergency rooms. The company, Med-Fax, created by David Grober in 1986, used the DECtalk on an IBM platform, making it one of the early cross platform applications (DEC to IBM). *DECtalk had a number of built-in voices which were identified by the following names: Perfect Paul (the default voice), Beautiful Betty, Huge Harry, Frail Frank, Kit the Kid, Rough Rita, Uppity Ursula, Doctor Dennis and Whispering Wendy. In addition the voices were editable by adjusting various parameters (such as throat size, crossover frequencies, etc.) *DECtalk understood phonetic spellings of words, allowing customized pronunciation of unusual words. These phonetic spellings could also include a tone indicator which DECtalk would use when enunciating the phonetic components. This allowed DECtalk to sing. *In addition, all the electronic voices in the movie '''Back to the Future II''' were created by personnel from the Digital Equipment Corporation's San Diego office, using the DECtalk [[Text-to-speech|TTS]] system. *DECtalk can be used as part of a [[speech generating device]] for those unable to speak. A notable user was [[Stephen Hawking]], who was unable to speak due to a combination of severe disabilities caused by [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis|ALS]] as well as an emergency [[tracheotomy]].<ref> {{cite web | last = Hawking | first = Stephen | title = Stephen Hawking and ALS | url = http://www.chninternational.com/stephen_hawking_and_als.htm | <!-- work = Compassionate Healthcare Network (CHN) --> | accessdate= 2009-08-10 }} (Originally published as: {{cite web | last = Hawking | first = Stephen | title = Disability - my experience with ALS | url = http://www.hawking.org.uk/disable/dindex.html | work = hawking.org.uk | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20000614043350/http://www.hawking.org.uk/disable/disable.html | archivedate = 2000-06-14 }}) </ref> Hawking used a version of the DECtalk voice synthesizer for several years<ref> {{cite web | last = Greenemeier | first = Larry | title = Getting Back the Gift of Gab: NexGen Handheld Computers Allow the Mute to Converse | url = http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=assistive-communication | work = Scientific American | date = 2009-08-10 | accessdate= 2009-08-10 }} </ref> and came to be associated with the unique voice of the device. In 2011, Hawking's research assistant Sam Blackburn said Hawking still used a version of DECtalk identified on its board as the "Calltext 5010" manufactured in 1988 by SpeechPlus, Inc.,<ref> {{cite web | last = Lange | first = Catherine de | title = The man who saves Stephen Hawking's voice | url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn21323-the-man-who-saves-stephen-hawkings-voice.html | work = New Scientist | date = 2011-12-30 | accessdate= 2013-06-09 }} </ref> because he identified with it and had not heard a voice he liked better. The CallText 5010 was still listed on Hawking's site {{as of|2015|lc=y}}.<ref> {{cite web | last = Hawking | first = Stephen | title = The Computer | url = http://www.hawking.org.uk/the-computer.html | work = hawking.org.uk | accessdate= 2015-03-01 }}</ref> A team from Cambridge (UK) and Palo Alto eventually emulated the workings of the CallText 5010 on a Raspberry Pi, which Hawking used from January 2018 to his death in March of that year.<ref> {{cite web | last = Fagone | first = Jason | title = The quest to save Stephen Hawking's voice | url = https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/The-Silicon-Valley-quest-to-preserve-Stephen-12759775.php | work = sfchronicle.com | accessdate= 2018-03-20 }} </ref> *The character "Dee Klatt" from [[Chipspeech]] was based on data from this device.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.plogue.com/products/chipspeech/ |title = Plogue - chipspeech :: Vintage speech synthesizer |work = PLOGUE - Music Software - Developers |accessdate= 2016-04-27 }}</ref> *In the sixth episode of [[Tales from the Darkside]], Mookie and Pookie, the voice of Kevin "Mookie" Anderson is created with a DECtalk.
